
[1]herald

   HER'ALD, n.

   1. An officer whose business was to denounce or proclaim war,to
   challenge to battle, to proclaim peace, and to bear messages from the
   commander of an army. Hence,

   2. A proclaimer; a publisher; as the herald of another's fame.

   3. A forerunner; a precursor; a harbinger.

   It was the lark, the herald of the morn.

   4. An officer in Great Britain, whose business is to marshal, order and
   conduct royal cavalcades, ceremonies at coronations, royal marriages,
   installations, creations of dukes and other nobles, embassies, funeral
   processions, declarations of war, proclamations of peace, &c.; also, to
   record and blazon the arms of the nobility and gentry, and to regulate
   abuses therein.

   5. Formerly applied by the French to a minstrel.

                 HER'ALD, v.t. To introduce, as by a herald.
